<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Hunters Armley rises 29%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEOFF DYER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hunters Armley, the commercial printer which last week expanded with the
purchase of a private Bristol-based printing company, increased pre-tax
profits by 29 per cent in the year to September 30.
Investment in new production facilities and the addition of more than 100
new customer accounts helped lift profits to Pounds 3.46m (Pounds 2.67m), on
turnover up 27 per cent at Pounds 41.1m (Pounds 32.2m).
Despite increases in paper prices of up to 60 per cent, operating margins
rose from 9 per cent to 9.2 per cent. Operating profit jumped 30 per cent to
Pounds 3.77m (Pounds 2.9m).
Mr Brian Sugden, managing director, said: 'Increased paper costs are an
opportunity not a threat for us, because they show that there is increased
demand.'
Capital expenditure of the group, which floated in December 1992, amounted
to Pounds 6.3m, including the installation of two new web offset presses at
the Bradford plant, which now has the same capacity as the Leeds plant.
A rights issue in May, which raised Pounds 9.4m, helped the group record a
net cash position of Pounds 3.06m, against net borrowings of Pounds 3.7m and
54 per cent gearing last time.
On December 5 it acquired Harlequin Colourprint, the Bristol-based sheet-fed
printer, for a maximum consideration of Pounds 4.4m. In the last financial
year Harlequin made pre-tax profits of Pounds 258,000 and has made profits
of more than Pounds 500,000 in the first nine months of this year.
Mr Sugden said that the group would be looking to make further acquisitions
of sheet-fed printers in London and Scotland.
Earnings per share were up 11 per cent at 10.01p (9.05p).
The proposed final dividend is 2.68p making 4p (3.75p) for the year, a 6.7
per cent increase.
</TEXT>
