<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Stanhope asks for standstill on debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stanhope, the property developer on the brink of collapse, will today ask
banks, meeting to decide its future, for a debt standstill of up to three
years.
The company was last night trying to arrange a deal which would offer the
banks full repayment of their Pounds 140m loans, with interest, at the end
of a standstill period.
Stanhope's existing loan facility runs out next Monday. The 16 banks led by
Barclays must decide whether to appoint receivers or give the company more
time to come up with a rescue package. The other rescue proposals for
Stanhope come from British Land, the property investment company headed by
Mr John Ritblat, and PosTel, the post and telecommunications pension fund
run by Mr Alastair Ross Goobey.
Both of these plans ask the banks to take a write-down of more than 20p in
the pound on their loans.
Stanhope's own proposal envisages the company's Pounds 5m-Pounds 10m a year
running costs would be met during the standstill period by an unknown
investor in return for an equity stake.
The total cost of funding the company through the period would be Pounds
25m-Pounds 30m, against a market capitalisation of less than Pounds 20m.
Before giving Stanhope more time to finalise the plan, the banks will want
to know the identity of the investor and haveassurances of sufficient
working capital.
Stanhope's main asset is its 50 per cent stake in Broadgate Properties,
which owns much of the Broadgate and Ludgate developments in the City of
London. Broadgate Properties' accounts, published in October, valued its
assets at Pounds 1bn and Stanhope's stake at Pounds 116m.
Forecasts carried out for the company by Jones Lang Wootton, the surveyors,
suggest that the value of Broadgate Properties' assets could rise to Pounds
1.4bn by June 1997.
While this would allow Stanhope to repay its loans at the end of any
standstill, assumptions about Broadgate's future value are based on
forecasts of rents which could be wrong.
Sources close to the talks yesterday said they expected the banks to give
the company more time. Stanhope's shares fell by 3p to 10p yesterday.
</TEXT>
