<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / IBM halts shipments of 'flawed chip' computers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines has halted shipments of computers containing
the Pentium microprocessor made by Intel, the world's leading supplier.
The move follows growing customer concern about a flaw in the chip that can
lead to miscalculations in some mathematical applications.
Intel's share price dropped yesterday after the decision, closing in New
York at Dollars 60 3/8 , down from Dollars 62 3/4 on Friday.
IBM is one of Intel's largest customers. Its action has strained relations
with the company - which revealed last month there were problems with the
microprocessor. Intel complained yesterday that IBM had refused to provide
details of its analysis of Pentium errors and gave no notice of its
decision.
The microprocessor fault has proved embarrassing for Intel, which has 90 per
cent of the world microprocessor market. It is running an Dollars 80m
(Pounds 53m) worldwide campaign to persuade personal computer users to buy
Pentium-based machines.
Other PC makers using the Pentium microprocessor include Compaq,
Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Gateway and Packard Bell. They have offered to
replace faulty chips, but IBM is alone in halting shipments. However, other
manufacturers may now feel obliged to follow IBM's lead.
IBM stressed it had no desire to exacerbate Intel's embarrassment or to gain
competitive advantage. 'IBM is not encouraging customers to switch to
different products,' it said. 'Our decision to halt shipments is based
solely on customer interests.'
Intel has argued that most computer users would never experience the fault
which, it said, was likely to occur only once every 27,000 years. The only
people likely to be affected, it said, were technologists such as aircraft
designers carrying out large computations.
IBM, however, said that its scientists had found that the risk of errors may
be higher. 'A user could face either significantly more errors, or no errors
at all. If an error occurs . . . it may have no effect or it may have
catastrophic effects.' Customers using common spreadsheet programs could
encounter errors once every 24 days. For a customer with 500 Pentium-based
PCs, this could result in as many as 20 mistakes a day.
Intel said it believed IBM's action was 'unwarranted' and added that it did
not expect to take a charge against fourth-quarter earnings because of any
repercussions from the flaw.
Court rules against IBM, Page 7
US stocks, Page 41
</TEXT>
