FT  13 DEC 94 / Letters to the Editor: Highest and lowest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From DAVID J. CRITCHLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Frank Blackaby (Letters: December 7) asks what the ratio between the
highest and lowest paid members of a company should be. It may be of
interest to know that in 1915 Admiral Jellicoe, who was described as the one
person who could lose the war in an afternoon, was paid Pounds 1,825 a year,
while an Ordinary Seaman earned Pounds 12 3s (Pounds 12.15) a year - a ratio
of 1:150. By 1917, the ratio had dropped to 1:105.
David J. Critchley
46 Station Road,
Winslow,
Buckingham,
MK18 3EH
