<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / People: Allied Leisure's team 'in place'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Allied Leisure, the ten-pin bowling group, hopes to have ended a year of
boardroom upheavals with the appointments of Neil Goulden, as managing
director, and Peter Molony as a non-executive.
Directors have been falling like skittles at Allied, which lost its chief
executive and other directors this year as it plunged into the red. In
September, it reported pre-tax losses of Pounds 30.1m for the 48 weeks to
June 19 after withdrawing from its nightclub businesses to refocus on its
ten-pin bowling operations.
Ken Scobie, who resigned as chief executive of Brent Walker in January 1993,
was appointed part-time chairman in September, replacing William Davis.
Damien Harte, appointed finance director just over a year ago, said
yesterday that Allied's management team is now complete. Goulden's major
task would be to consolidate the core bowling business and take it forward.
Goulden, 41, is currently chief executive at Letheby &amp; Christopher, the
division of Compass that specialises in sports and event catering. During
his six-year tenure, Letheby's turnover has doubled to Pounds 40m. His
20-year experience of the leisure industry includes stints with Ladbroke and
with Grand Metropolitan at the Chef &amp; Brewer and Berni Inns chains.
Bowling contributes less than half Allied's turnover, which is made up from
food and drink operations, and from video machines.
Molony, who was the longest serving member of the Rolls-Royce board when he
left in 1986, previously worked as finance director of Scottish &amp; Newcastle
Breweries and as Accountant General to the Post Office.
</TEXT>
