<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Computer highway wins first customer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 40m commercial information superhighway carried by electricity
pylons and existing underground cables announced its first customer
yesterday - a live network for training keyhole surgeons remotely from
operating theatres in St James's Hospital in Leeds, Ian Hamilton Fazey
writes.
Torch Telecom, a joint venture between Yorkshire Electricity and Kingston
Communications, said the technology was capable of transmitting engineering
or textile designs, high-quality faxes, thousands of telephone calls or
large amounts of computer data.
The network - being marketed to business and big public-sector customers -
is developed around what Torch calls a 'backbone ring' linking Leeds,
Wakefield, Huddersfield, Halifax and Bradford in West Yorkshire. Secondary
circuits will allow local access throughout Leeds, Bradford, Sheffield and
Hull.
Video-link medical applications of fibre optics elsewhere use the telephone
network. Torch said its system had a bandwidth capacity of 155 megabits per
second - compared with 2Mbit/s using upgraded telephone lines - giving
better pictures or more reliable data transmission.
The keyhole surgery system, which has been on trial for three months, will
soon be improved to 622 Mbit/s, allowing 12 operations to be transmitted
simultaneously from the hospital to the Leeds Institute for Minimally
Invasive Therapy.
As well as enabling trainees to see better, voice links allow them to
communicate with surgeons as though everyone was in the operating theatre.
Torch said its network would improve inward investment prospects by
improving the business communications infrastructure and helping
locally-based companies reduce costs.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Torch Telecom.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4899 Communications Services, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
