<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Report urges steps to end benefit fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER, Employment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strong measures to prevent benefit fraud have been advocated by Mr Frank
Field, the Labour MP, in an effort to advance the debate on unemployment,
which he says is 'dominated by ideologues of left and right'.
He has published a report which 'rejects the Conservatives' tinkering with
benefits and calls for a totally new approach to welfare: one that aims to
reduce the numbers on welfare rather than punish those forced to depend on
it'.
Mr Field, who chairs the Commons committee on social security, has written
the report with Mr Matthew Owen, a Liberal Democrat economist.
The document, funded by Nuffield Foundation, says:
Claimants suspected of defrauding the public should be required to register
on a number of occasions each day with their local Jobcentre to ensure that
they are undertaking adequate job searches and are maintaining and upgrading
their skills.
Employers should have to register all long-term openings with the employment
service so that claimants can be offered real jobs before losing their
benefits.
Taxpayers will need to fund an employment service adequate to meet the
challenge of a flexible labour market where continuing education is a basic
requirement for all workers, no less for those in work than those in the
dole queue.
Government must wipe out benefit fraud as a start to building the
foundations for full employability in Britain.
Government must start viewing training schemes as opportunities for
self-improvement and the betterment of claimants - and not as a means of
punishing them.
Beyond Punishment. Institute of Community Studies, 18 Victoria Park Sq,
London E2 9PZ. Pounds 9.95.
</TEXT>
