<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Fall in assisted homeless families
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of families accepted as homeless by local authorities has fallen
to its lowest level for more than two years, official figures showed
yesterday.
But the figures coincided with a report that Britain faced 'new youth
homelessness crisis' with growing numbers of women and younger people on the
streets.
Mr David Curry, housing minister, said the new data reflected the success of
government measures to increase the supply of affordable housing and to
persuade local authorities to move away from using bed and breakfast as
temporary accommodation.
A survey of those staying at the charity Centrepoint's emergency shelters,
however, found the proportion of young women up from 26 per cent to 43 per
cent in the past seven years, with a 38 per cent rise in the number of
16-year-olds and 17-year-olds.
A survey of 1,500 under-25s at six charity projects shows that 44 per cent
were from ethnic minorities.
More than four in 10 of the homeless had no income at all, because those
aged 16 and 17 cannot claim benefit.
The official figures, from the Department of the Environment, put the number
of homeless households accepted for rehousing in England in the last quarter
at 31,270.
In the year ending September 1994 homelessness acceptances were 125,640  - 9
per cent down from the year ending September 1993 and a reduction of 19,440
from the peak annual total of 145,080 for the year ending March 1992.
</TEXT>
