<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / A union rallying cry echoes in Europe: Robert Taylor reports
on the TUC's break with tradition in advocating workplace rights for all
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Workplace rights for all workers looks likely to be the new rallying cry for
Britain's trade unions as the TUC's new approach takes British unions into
the mainstream of European thought on industrial relations.
The new approach may offend some union feelings. Many have traditionally
opposed the provision of rights for everybody, fearing that people would not
feel the need to join a union to enjoy protection at work.
But union leaders involved in the TUC's task group on workplace
representation say that statutory representation for all should encourage
unions to develop new strategies for growth and influence.
They believe unions will retain a strong workplace presence as unions still
do in Sweden and Germany, where such systems operate successfully.
But the TUC is not simply copying mainland European practice. As Mr Bill
Morris, the head of the task group, explained to German and Swedish union
officials and employers, UK unions want to see how the voluntary principle
of trade union membership can best be linked with satisfactory arrangements
for statutory representation.
This will require a complex balance between voluntarism and regulation, but
it looks as though the TUC has achieved a remarkable degree of consensus
among union leaders - from Mr Tony Dubbins of the GPMU print union on the
left to Mr Bill Jordan, AEEU craft union president, on the right.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, has been helped in his efforts to win
over sceptics in the unions by the government's almost wholly negative
attitude to the European Union's social affairs agenda, symbolised by its
opt-out from the social protocol of the Maastricht treaty.
Recent decisions against the UK by the European Court of Justice have said
that employees must have adequate information and consultation rights under
EU directives covering collective redundancies and the legal transfer of
undertakings from one company to another.
The task group has accepted that what it proposes needs to be compatible
with the directives as interpreted by the European Court of Justice, which
means recognising adequate protection for all workers without undermining
trade union influence and collective bargaining.
The kind of process the TUC has in mind is based on how the new EU works
council directive is likely to develop. This provides information and
consultation rights in bigger trans-national enterprises.
Although the UK may have opted out of the directive's provisions as applied
to Britain, more than 100 British-owned companies are likely to have such
councils in place in their businesses in the next three years. More
important, the directive shows the TUC how to integrate the voluntary
approach with statutory regulation.
Once the works council directive comes into force representatives of either
management or workers can establish a 'special negotiating body' to discuss
what kind of works council the company will establish. Only if the employer
refuses to do this, or negotiations fail for some other reason, is a legally
enforceable fallback provision for councils applicable.
The proposed negotiating body will be in line with national law and
customary practice in each EU member state. The TUC says this should favour
trade union representation in Britain and include full-time officials. The
task group envisages a similar process for the creation of workplace
committees in every company in the UK.
The TUC position is a bold step forward but it is likely to arouse
widespread opposition from employers. It is not a sharp break with the past,
however. The task group has been ingenious in weaving together the
regulatory and voluntary traditions. It provides a positive way forward by
suggesting a voice for all employees in Britain's workplaces, where surveys
suggest people are feeling increasingly insecure, and offers a chance for a
trade union revival.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8631 Labor Organizations.
    P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
