<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / More signs of inflation pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further signs of inflationary pressure were revealed yesterday, with figures
showing that manufacturers are increasing prices at the factory gate, while
raw material costs are rising at their fastest for 18 months.
The core measure of the output prices of manufacturers, which excludes
volatile goods such as food, beverages, tobacco and petroleum, rose a
seasonally adjusted 0.4 per cent between October and November.
According to the Central Statistical Office the annual rise in the core
measure of output prices was 2.6 per cent in the 12 months to November. But
the pace of growth is accelerating. Prices in the three months to November
were 4 per cent higher than in the previous three months, on an annualised
basis.
Analysts saw the strength of yesterday's producer price figures as evidence
that the chancellor was right to sanction a half percentage point increase
in base rates last week. But it is not yet clear whether higher producer
prices would be passed on to consumers in the high street.
Mr Adam Cole, UK economist at James Capel, pointed out that low wage growth,
combined with strong productivity, was offsetting rising commodity prices.
He said manufacturers' overall cost bill was broadly flat, so that the aim
behind the factory gate price rises was to improve margins. With consumers
reluctant to pay higher prices, the result was that 'retail margins are
clearly getting squeezed very heavily,' he added.
The overall level of output prices rose an unadjusted 0.1 per cent between
October and November, for an annual rise of 2.4 per cent. There were
particularly sharp jumps in the prices of pulp and paper products, chemicals
and in paper and plastic products.
Meanwhile, manufacturers' raw material costs are rising even faster than
factory gate prices. Input prices rose an unadjusted 2.4 per cent between
October and November, for an annual rise of 7.9 per cent, up from 6.9 per
cent in October. This was the highest annual rate since March last year.
The main component in the unadjusted rise was the winter increase in the
price of electricity. The seasonally adjusted index rose just 0.7 per cent
on the month, for an 8.1 per cent annual increase. Higher milk prices also
played a part, contributing 0.4 percentage points of the monthly rise.
The cost of many commodities rose substantially in the year to November,
with coffee more than doubling in price.
</TEXT>
