<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / 'Bazaar' plan angers ex-GLC boss
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A former Tory leader of the Greater London Council protested yesterday
against new plans for its former headquarters, County Hall, saying the
building was in danger of being turned into 'an eastern bazaar'.
Lord Plummer urged ministers at Lords question time to ensure that the
redevelopment was carried out in accordance with its planning permission.
The original proposals from the building's owners, the Japanese property
company Shirayama, included provision - recently abandoned - for a
600-bedroom hotel. It is now planned to turn the building into a Pacific
Asia centre.
Lord Plummer, GLC leader from 1967-73, told peers: 'County Hall occupies a
prime location in the heart of the capital and should not be allowed to
lapse into an eastern bazaar.'
Lord Inglewood, for the government, said it was for Lambeth council, not
ministers, to ensure the planning rules were observed.
But he added that English Heritage was satisfied that the works accorded
with the planning consents.
Tory Lord Beloff said it would have been far better if the building had been
taken over by the London School of Economics as a 'major educational
edifice'.
Baroness Hollis of Heigham, for Labour, said two commercial schemes for the
building had collapsed, the Shirayama deal had been a 'shambles' and
possible future use by the public sector should be considered.
But Lord Inglewood said: 'Anyone who owns a building and has planning
permission for it is entitled to implement that permission.'
</TEXT>
