FT  13 DEC 94 / Major's joke starts a row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major, the prime minister, threw a bone to his Eurosceptic rebels
yesterday, and promptly found himself embroiled in a dogfight.
Answering questions in the Commons after a statement on the European Union
summit in Essen, Mr Major joked that few other heads of government were
subject to the rigorous questioning faced by UK prime ministers in the
Commons.
As Tories cheered, he added: 'Indeed I have to say that some of my fellow
heads of government could scarcely find their way to their parliament with a
guide dog.'
Mr Major's joke backfired as Labour MPs demanded he withdraw his
'gratuitously insulting' comment. Mr Tony Banks (Newham NW) warned that his
remarks were likely to develop into 'a story throughout Europe'. He added:
'Perhaps they have got their parliaments rather under greater control than
you have your own.'
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, wrote to Mr Major, saying his
remarks risked undermining Britain's standing in the Union.
