<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Benn is voted off committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The House of Commons decided last night by a majority of 129 (181-52) to
remove Mr Tony Benn from the privileges committee which is examining the
'cash for questions' affair.
An unrepentant Mr Benn, Labour MP for Chesterfield, said that he had been
justified in breaching the rules of the committee and the House by
publishing his own account of proceedings which took place in private.
He insisted that the public was entitled to know about charges which had
been said to involve 'bribery, fraud and corruption'.
Mr Benn said he did not know whether the allegations were true, but they had
gravely damaged the democratic process.
He said the public would be wondering if some MPs were using their position
not to represent their constituents but to 'pedal their influence for
money'.
'If the House decides to retreat behind its traditional practice of working
in secret, it will be making a very great mistake that could damage
parliament and public confidence in us,' he said.
His demand that statements made by members of the committee when
deliberating over their conclusions - as well as evidence by witnesses  -
should be published was opposed from both sides of the House.
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, argued that the maintenance of
secrecy during the deliberation process was an essential element in helping
to achieve the consensus which frequently led to a majority report.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow leader of the House, was joined by Mr Peter Shore,
Labour MP for Bethnal Green and Stepney in suggesting that, as with juries
in criminal trials, it would be wrong for the deliberative processes of the
committee to be conducted in public.
Mr David Alton, for the Liberal Democrats, complained that Mr Benn's
deliberate action in breaching the rules of the House had delayed the
inquiry into a matter which had brought the reputation of parliament into
disrepute.
The committee's investigation centres on the action of Mr Graham Riddick,
Conservative MP for Colne Valley and Mr David Tredinnick, Conservative MP
for Bosworth, in agreeing to accept payment for tabling questions in the
Commons.
</TEXT>
