<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / PO and union clash over strike impact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER, Employment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Post Office managers and the postal workers' union clashed last night about
the impact of yesterday's 24-hour strike, which shut more than 100 main
offices.
Managers said the walkout was a complete flop, saying only 800 workers
joined in. The Union of Communication Workers said the response was
tremendous and accused the Post Office of using managers and casual workers
to cover for strikers.
The strike was in protest at the closure of hundreds of main offices since
1989 and their transfer to franchised stores or supermarkets.
The union said yesterday that franchised post offices made more mistakes
than the main offices they replaced. The UCW said a leaked document covering
south-east London showed cash accounting mistakes in a franchised post
office in the three months to July were 78 per cent worse than the Post
Office's target.
Mr Alan Johnson, general secretary of the UCW, said: 'It is ridiculous for
the Post Office to claim that by shunting our post offices into the back of
supermarkets, service is improved. They are misleading the public and their
own documents prove it.'
The union said it had overwhelming public support for the strike and for the
campaign to halt closures.
According to the UCW 95 per cent of those who voted to strike did not work
yesterday, with the action hitting London, Bristol, Glasgow, Liverpool,
parts of Wales and Cornwall.
The Post Office said 647 of the country's 764 main offices were open. It
added that the number of main offices was almost exactly the same as four
years ago, with those moving to retail outlets frequently opening longer and
having better access.
The union has complained about 'back-door privatisation'. It says half of
the country's main post offices have closed since 1989. Mr Johnson said:
'Hundreds more will close by 1999 unless the rot is stopped. We are
demanding a complete halt to all closures from today.'
Collections and deliveries of Christmas post were not hit by the industrial
action, which the union is threatening to repeat in the new year.
</TEXT>
