<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Banks' risk assessment under scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England has established a specialist supervisory team to assess
individual banks' ability to monitor how much risk they take on in their
securities business.
The team, set up in August, will not be making formal assessment visits
until January 1996, but it has been making 'prototype visits' to examine the
extent to which banks monitor their own risks.
A Bank official said: 'Our overall impression is that the standards of risk
management are satisfactory but we need to look at them very carefully.'
Banks with inadequate practices will not be allowed to carry on securities
business until their risk-measurement and monitoring are improved.
The unit will be looking at the models used by banks to measure how the
value of their securities holdings change with other market movements such
as interest rates. While bigger banks with strong information technology
systems are likely to monitor risk closely, there is concern that some risk
measurement systems are rudimentary.
The Bank of England will not tell banks what model to use. Instead, it will
evaluate whether the model is sufficient to measure the risks that the
individual bank is likely to take on, and the rigour with which it adheres
to that model.
The creation of the new unit was prompted by the advent of the capital
adequacy directive, an EU move to standardise the capital requirements which
banking and securities institutions must hold in respect of the risks they
take on.
For the first time, UK banks will have to hold capital in respect of
so-called 'market risks', the risks that the value of securities they hold
will fall or rise sharply in line with interest rates.
Until now the Bank of England has been concerned mostly with 'counterparty
risk', the risk that a debtor will not repay on time, and with the risk
inherent in foreign exchange positions.
The securities and futures authority, which monitors the securities
positions of securities and investment banks, has been evaluating its own
members' risk models for some time.
Where regulators feel those models are inadequate, the models will have to
be changed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
