<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / More dialogue planned for spending round
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury hopes to improve the system of negotiating the annual public
spending round by stepping up its early contacts with the spending
ministries, Mr Jonathan Aitken, the Treasury chief secretary, said
yesterday.
He told the Commons Treasury and civil service committee that negotiations,
particularly in the preliminary stages of the round, were rather like a
'choreographed Victorian minuet', with some meetings 'a bit like those
between North Korea and South Korea'.
He said it would be more helpful if there was greater dialogue between
ministers and officials from the Treasury, and spending ministers and their
officials, before the round started in earnest in September. He hoped to
introduce 'away days or listening days' for ministers and officials from
both sides.
Mr Aitken had to answer charges levelled by Labour, Liberal Democrat and
Tory MPs, that the government's achievements in controlling public spending
were more apparent than real.
He rejected suggestions that the government had failed in its objectives
because the control total of departmental spending was expected to increase
in real terms in the 1994-95 financial year compared with plans in last
year's Budget for a fall.
Mr Aitken stressed that the increase reflected lower than expected inflation
in the current financial year, which resulted in spending plans fixed in
cash terms showing real increases.
To change these plans during the year to take account of low inflation would
'cause chaos' for managers in areas such as the health service.
Mr Aitken was also downbeat on the prospects for cutting a swathe through
the burgeoning social security budget. Reforms such as changes to
unemployment benefit, statutory sick pay, invalidity benefit and housing
benefit would have a positive effect in the long term, he said.
But cutting social security was not like cutting defence. About 90 per cent
of non-cyclical social security spending was entitlement-driven while 44 per
cent comprised pensions and income support for the elderly, which was
covered by manifesto commitments.
</TEXT>
