<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Redwood criticises quango for past lapses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An inquiry commissioned by the Welsh Development Agency has shown what Mr
John Redwood, Welsh secretary, described yesterday as 'serious lapses in
management control over its joint venture activities'.
The report, by Grant Thornton, the accountancy firm, looked at the agency's
involvement two years ago in a development project in Aberdare, Mid
Glamorgan. It had been alleged that the agency competed with the private
sector for land.
A joint venture board had been set up in 1991 between the WDA, Cynon Valley
borough council and Mid Glamorgan county council. Grant Thornton said the
agency should have considered a joint venture with a private developer,
rather than be seen to displace the private sector. It considered the agency
failed to ensure the best value for money in buying land subsequently sold
for a Tesco superstore.
Mr Redwood told the Commons in a written answer that the report showed 'no
evidence of improper pecuniary gain or collusion by any of the parties'. But
he said Mr David Rowe-Beddoe, who became WDA chairman last year, 'agrees
with me that the former management's conduct fell short of the standards we
expect'. The WDA was chaired at the time by Dr Gwyn Jones.
Mr Barry Hartop, who became WDA chief executive this year, said yesterday:
'The criticisms of the agency's former procedures are accepted and we have
already taken remedial action to improve controls and ensure transparency on
dealings involving third parties.'
The Welsh secretary noted that Cynon Valley council had not allowed Grant
Thornton access to certain papers. 'I hope those concerned will study the
report carefully and, where appropriate, carry out their own investigation.'
He said it would be for the district auditor to respond to requests for an
inquiry into the council's activities. The council did not comment last
night.
Mr Redwood said Mr Hartop had informed the Commons public accounts committee
about other past matters, including the underwriting of share issues, the
engagement of consultants, redundancy and pension payments, procurement
issues and breaches of delegated authority. He said: 'Some of these
instances of non-compliance have continued until earlier this year.'
It has been disclosed that the WDA made a net loss of Pounds 150,000 on
underwriting share issues of privatised and Welsh companies. Underwriting
stopped in 1991. Mr Redwood said he had told the WDA that this was not an
appropriate role.
</TEXT>
