<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / Benn warns Commons on sleaze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The House of Commons is on trial over its handling of recent allegations of
sleaze against MPs, Mr Tony Benn said last night as he tried to persuade MPs
not to vote to remove him from the powerful Commons privileges committee.
The veteran leftwing Labour MP said the real issue at stake was not his
removal from the committee, which is investigating allegations of
misbehaviour against two Tory MPs, but whether it was right for the
committee's deliberations to be reported.
'If the House decides to retreat behind its traditional practice of working
in secret, it will be making a very great mistake that could damage
parliament and public confidence in us,' he said.
'It is the House which is ultimately responsible for having set itself such
low standards of public conduct.'
Speaking before the vote, Mr Benn set out a six-point blueprint for raising
standards in public life. He called for the use of 'parliamentary influence'
in return for payment to be treated as a breach of privilege and for the
rules governing the private interests of ministers to apply to all MPs.
He said the powers to investigate MPs charged with a breach of these rules
should be transferred to the courts. It should be made illegal for any
outside company or organisation to pay MPs for 'parliamentary services
designed to win influence'. It would put 'a complete stop' to the peddling
of influence.
The former Labour cabinet minister said if the steps he proposed were taken,
it would not prevent MPs from maintaining their professions. Nor would it
prevent political contributions being paid to candidates or parties - 'under
proper safeguards'.
Mr Benn was voted off the committee last month by the 17 MPs who sit on it
after he gave the press an account of the discussions at its last meeting.
He can only be formally removed after a vote by the entire House.
It is understood that only two MPs - Mr Bill Michie, the MP for Sheffield
Heeley, and Mr Benn himself - voted against the expulsion. One Labour
committee member said that he backed the principle of opening up some
committee sessions but Mr Benn's policy of giving the press an account of
private sessions could not be justified.
</TEXT>
