<HEADLINE>
FT  13 DEC 94 / NZ pursues monetary restraint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The New Zealand Reserve Bank will continue to lean towards monetary
restraint because of the country's strong economic growth, running at 6.1
per cent, the governor, Mr Don Brash, said early today. The Reserve Bank is
facing its most testing time since it was placed in charge of monetary
policy in 1989 because of strong growth and concerns about inflation
pressures. Mr Brash, who has signed a price stability contract with the
government under which he must keep inflation below 2 per cent, agreed his
'job was on the line' if his handling of monetary policy failed. He said he
had decided against further tightening monetary policy at present because of
sharp rises in interest rates over the past two weeks. Short-term rates have
risen by around 1.25 points to 10 per cent, matched by a strong lift in the
value of the dollar. This followed a statement to market dealers in late
November that the bank wanted firmer monetary conditions.
'By enforcing restraint the bank is aiming to ensure more steady and
sustained economic growth and avoid the disruptive boom-bust cycle New
Zealand has endured in the past, ' Mr Brash said. He told a news conference
he expected trading banks would now lift their home mortgage rates, but it
was up to them to decide much.
</TEXT>
