FT  13 DEC 94 / Ukraine energy chief loses job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Leonid Kuchma yesterday dismissed Ukraine's senior energy official
for failing to make payments on arrears of Dollars 713.5m (Pounds 457m) owed
for gas supplies from Turkmenistan. By sacking Mr Mykhailo Kovalko, chairman
of the state oil and gas committee, Mr Kuchma sent a strong signal, both to
his own bureaucracy and to the west, that he is serious about pursuing the
radical economic reforms he unveiled in the autumn. Ukraine has won
substantial foreign aid to back these reforms, much of it earmarked to help
pay for the fuel it receives from Russia and Turkmenistan. Mr Kuchma accused
Mr Kovalko of failing to make payments due under a seven-year debt
rescheduling agreement Ukraine reached with Turkmenistan last month. Kiev
has since paid Turkmenistan Dollars 41m, using some of the Dollars 371m in
aid from the International Monetary Fund.
Ukraine also owes Russia about Dollars 1.4bn, much of it to Gazprom. The
Russian gas giant has no choice but to supply Ukraine because 97 per cent of
its gas exports flow through a Ukrainian pipeline - a serious defect in the
eyes of potential western investors. Mr Kuchma has insisted that he will not
tolerate corruption in the potentially lucrative energy sector.
</TEXT>
