<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Profits drop causes global ripple of fear: Hoist with its
own petard - Southwest Airlines tumbles as fare war takes its toll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Southwest Airlines is hardly among the biggest or best-known airlines: yet
the extraordinary influence of this Texas-based US carrier was felt around
the world at the end of last week.
Global airline stocks took a battering after Southwest announced that
fourth-quarter profits were going to be 'substantially below' its net income
of Dollars 38.4m (Pounds 23.4m) a year earlier. In Europe, KLM's shares
dropped nearly 4 per cent on Friday, and Lufthansa's fell by 2.2 per cent.
On the face of it, the reaction was unjustified: Southwest's problems stem
from conditions peculiar to the US domestic market. But investors were left
wondering: 'If Southwest, of all airlines, is in trouble, what hope is there
for the rest of them?'
Southwest's fourth-quarter downturn ends a remarkable period of profits
growth for the company - remarkable because it has contrasted so sharply
with the heavy losses suffered by the rest of the US airline industry in
recent years.
Southwest has prospered because of its low costs. The airline specialises in
short-haul shuttle services on high-density routes in the US. There are no
in-flight meals or other frills; flights are frequent and turnarounds are
fast; and employees are hard-working, flexible and enthusiastic. As a
result, South-west's operating costs per available seat mile are just 7.1
cents - 19 per cent below the US industry average of 8.8 cents.
Low costs have enabled Southwest to grow rapidly in the deregulated US
market by charging rock-bottom fares. Expanding from its home territory of
Texas, it has spread across the southern states and has become the biggest
flight operator within California. Last year it began an assault on the
north-east by offering flights on the Baltimore-Chicago and
Baltimore-Cleveland routes at up to 85 per cent less than existing fares.
Southwest's strategy has led to a revolution in US air travel, at least on
short-haul routes. It has turned flying into a low-cost, high-volume
commodity business. Taking a flight on many routes in the US today is like
catching a bus: seats are unassigned and the service is rudimentary, but the
fare is cheap.
The trouble for Southwest is that other US carriers have responded to this
transformation by trying to mimic its formula. In markets where Southwest
operates, they have slashed fares in an attempt to keep market share. In
California, United Airlines has set up an operation called United Shuttle to
compete directly with Southwest. On the east coast, Southwest is slugging it
out in a three-cornered contest with Continental Airlines and USAir.
Until recently, the main victims of these fare wars had been Southwest's
competitors. Forced to match Southwest's low fares but lacking Southwest's
low costs, they had incurred heavy losses on routes where the competition
was strong.
The other US carriers, however, are working to get their costs down. A year
ago, South-west's operating costs per available seat mile were 26 per cent
below the industry average. Today, at 19 per cent, the gap is still wide,
but it is narrowing.
So does the fourth-quarter profits downturn indicate that the party is over
for Southwest? Not according to the company. On Friday, it said the biggest
factor behind the downturn had been the cost of integrating Morris Air, a
regional carrier based in Salt Lake City which it bought a year ago but
which has only recently been absorbed at an operational level.
Still, Southwest acknowledged that fare competition had played a role. Other
airlines were matching its fares on routes where they competed, the company
said, so it had held a number of special offers during the quarter. 'This is
as close as you can get to war in a peacetime environment,' a spokesman
remarked.
Southwest said some of its fare cuts had probably been too steep and it
would not be repeating them; and with Morris Air now fully integrated, it
expected profits to bounce back in next year's first quarter. 'We feel very
confident that growth will be back in line with what shareholders are used
to,' it said.
In the longer term, Southwest insists that it will remain one jump ahead of
other airlines by getting its own costs even lower. Next month, for example,
its pilots will be asked to ratify a highly unusual 10-year labour contract
under which they will get no wage increases for the next five years, instead
receiving share options.
Whether or not Southwest's optimism is justified, the outlook for the rest
of the US industry remains poor. With too many aircraft chasing too few
passengers, cut-throat fare competition looks set to continue and only the
lowest-cost carriers have any hope of doing well.
To the extent that the US air travel market today offers a glimpse of the
rest of the world's tomorrow, the reaction of global airline stocks to last
week's events was perhaps, after all, understandable.
</TEXT>
