<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Aid unlikely for main rail lines: Government subsidies to be
aimed at rural and branch services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's main line rail services will be expected to pay their own way so
that government subsidies can be concentrated on maintaining rural lines and
branch services, an announcement on Wednesday is likely to make clear.
The details of the passenger service requirements - the minimum timetable
that must be run to win government subsidy - are expected to create a
political furore because they will be seen as reducing services.
The timetable regulations to be unveiled by Mr Roger Salmon, railway
franchising director responsible for the sale of British Rail's passenger
train service, will show that operators must provide only an hourly service
on their main inter-city routes compared with the present half-hour
frequency on many main lines.
But Mr Salmon will argue that the train operators will have a commercial
interest in running services as frequently as possible and that services
will be maintained at least at present levels. InterCity services were the
most profitable part of BR.
If the franchising director were to expect train operators to guarantee a
half-hourly service, he would also have to promise to subsidise them if they
proved unprofitable. This would drain funds from the rural and branch lines,
many of which require considerable subsidies.
The timetable requirements are also expected to show that the franchising
director is not prepared to subsidise continuation of all sleeper services
between Scotland and England.
The franchising director has been allocated government subsidy to meet the
Pounds 2.2bn of track access charges to be paid by the 24 train operating
companies being created from BR.
Critics of rail privatisation have predicted the break-up of rail services
will lead to a decline in the quality and frequency of services. Sir Bob
Reid, BR chairman, and train user groups say the bureaucracy involved in the
new fragmented railway and the impact of the signalworkers' strike have
already led to reduced services.
But Mr Salmon is expected to point out that there has been no guarantee of
levels of services in the past and that the timetable arrangements included
in passenger service requirements represent an improvement on the previous
situation. The service requirements lay down frequency of trains and the
time of the first and last service.
If the timetable is laid down in excessive detail, Mr Salmon believes, train
operators will not have sufficient commercial freedom.
</TEXT>
