<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Observer: Ho ho avenue
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ho Chi Minh still lives - on the streets of Calcutta. Though probably not
for much longer.
West Bengal state, long a bastion of Indian communism, is trying to shed its
hard-line image in an effort to attract private capital. The authorities
have therefore invited companies based in an electronics park to have local
streets named after their founders.
Siemens - which helped instal the first telegraph connection between
Calcutta and London 126 years ago - was approached first.
One of the few cities left in the world that still celebrates the
anniversary of the Russian October revolution with posters of Marx and
Lenin, Calcutta is now to have a new street - Werner von Siemens.
Names of communist worthies adorning other streets are so far intact; Jyoti
Basu, the veteran chief minister, must tread carefully.
