<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mondays tend to be disturbing on television - in a deliberate,
thought-provoking, thoroughly worthy way. Tonight's double dose of
perturbation starts with World in Action (8.30pm ITV). Those who are
sceptical about the art of 'psychological profiling' will be intrigued by
this encounter with Paul Britton, apparently nicknamed 'Cracker' by his
colleagues (after the Robbie Coltrane character, I hasten to add). His role
in the trial of Colin Stagg for the murder of Rachel Nickell sparked
controversy about the role of this American neo-science. The whole practice
comes over as a new and still untried toy open to abuses unless rigorously
controlled.
Control is desperately needed in the killing of wildlife in Nepal (among
other places). In the Wild (9pm ITV) engineers a meeting between Bob Hoskins
and the tiger. Regrettably perhaps, Hoskins' chances of survival are
considerably healthier than the quadruped's. The programme ranges through
the pressures on the big cats and reminds us that species have already
become extinct in the past quarter-century.
</TEXT>
