FT  12 DEC 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV Editor, Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lawyers will be dancing in the streets at the thought of the government's
proposal to have British Rail broken down into 80 companies. The contract
work will be the largest legal job in the country, with 360 different
agreements for Scotland alone. Panorama (Monday, 9.30-10.10pm, BBC1)
investigates whether the plan will hit the buffers before the next election,
and reveals why Cecil Parkinson's first reaction, when he saw the
privatisation plans, was 'My God]'.
Carlton turns the arc lights on Tinseltown tots in Hollywood Kids
(Wednesday, 9.00-10.00pm, ITV), which talks to child stars and the children
of stars. Plastic surgery is common among prepubescents, and infants are
kitted out in Christian Dior romper suits, as a string of self-publicists
tells us. This new series consists largely of talking heads, but the things
they talk about are so extraordinary, the visual tedium goes unnoticed.
Rocket scientists are being consulted on how to calculate the odds on the
financial futures market, with everyone wanting to pile into the sector.
Assignment (Saturday, 7.20-8.05pm, BBC2) looks at how hedge funds play the
derivatives market and asks if new regulations are needed in order to avoid
last year's market turmoil.
