<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / FT Guide to UK telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The telephone business used to be dull and predictable; suddenly it's
exciting and confusing. What has happened?
Two things; first, the privatisation of British Telecommunications and the
subsequent liberalisation of the telephone business back in 1984. The
government created first a duopoly - BT plus Mercury Communications - to
bring an element of competition into what had been a monopoly. In 1991,
after a duopoly review, it decided to open the market further, allowing
other companies to bid for operator's licences. Some 57 new licences have
since been granted. At about the same time, changes in the rules allowed
cable television companies to offer telephone services.
Second, an explosion of technological advances, including digital - computer
language - transmission, which is making possible affordable services, such
as call waiting, call diversion and call barring, not to mention video
telephony and multimedia.
So if cable companies can offer telephone services, BT can transmit
television programs, I suppose?
Not quite. The concession to the cable companies was necessary to encourage
them to make the big investment in the infrastructure required. Allowing BT
to transmit TV programmes would destroy that advantage. So BT is forbidden
to broadcast entertainment until at least 2001. But it is allowed to
transmit on-demand services, hence its experiment in the south east of
England with video-on-demand, home shopping and home banking.
Mercury seems to be in trouble; how did it get it so wrong?During the
duopoly period, Mercury concentrated on skimming the cream from business
traffic on long-distance and international routes, helped by BT's ponderous
inflexibility at that time. But BT was handicapped by a formula which
required it to hold its prices to a number of percentage points below the
rate of inflation (currently the retail price index minus 7 1/2 per cent).
The price cap encouraged efficiency at BT, which now offers prices little
different from Mercury's. Mercury neglected to exploit other, potentially
lucrative market niches. Small fleet-of-foot competitors have emerged to
occupy niche markets Mercury could have cultivated. Now, squeezed on all
sides, it is forced to cut staff and services.
Who are these new companies in the telecoms business?
Cable companies such as Cable London, which covers the area around Camden
and Hackney in London, or Northwest Cable, covering Wigan and Barnsley, are
one category. Their network provides the connection to the home or office
and they use a carrier, typically Mercury, to provide long-distance
services.
Then there are utilities looking for a way into the telecoms market;
Energis, for example, set up by the National Grid Company, provides
long-distance services over fibre-optic cables wound round its power lines.
WorldCom is representative of a third category. A US company, it set up in
London in 1991 and resells international lines to big business at a
discount.
What about BT's position in the market?
BT remains the dominant player with over 80 per cent of the UK market. It
alone has a mature network covering the entire country with connections into
most homes. It complains bitterly about the regulatory restraints on its
behaviour and pricing freedom. Oftel, the telecoms regulator, has little
sympathy with this view.
Is telecoms becoming an international business?
Inevitably yes, driven by the communications needs of large international
companies. There is a race to become the leading 'global supercarrier',
managing telecoms around the globe for these companies. The leader is
probably Concert, operated by BT and MCI of the US, but AT&amp;T's Worldsource,
and Atlas, operated by US Sprint, Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom is not
far behind.
What does last week's Oftel document mean?
The regulatory regime, designed to promote competitiveness in the UK market
in an orderly fashion, has not been fully overhauled for a decade. The Oftel
document is meant to open up a discussion which could lead to a more open,
competitive market, where BT would have more freedom to set prices but all
the players would have to obey new, tough competition rules.
And the future?
Prices have fallen substantially over the past decade and are likely to
continue downwards, driven by competition and technology. There is a much
interest in Ionica, a Cambridge company promising even cheaper voice
telephony through radio links into the home.
But customers might not find their telecoms bills decreasing as much as they
might anticipate; every operator is looking for new and attractive services
to encourage more telephone calls.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
