FT  12 DEC 94 / Support rallies on Channel 4 funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jeremy Isaacs, founding chief executive of Channel 4, has launched a
campaign to overturn the channel's controversial funding formula, Raymond
Snoddy writes.
Campaigners say the effect of a formula intended by the 1990 Broadcasting
Act to protect Channel 4's remit to innovate 'is that a minority channel
subsidises the shareholders of the ITV companies to the tune of some Pounds
50m a year'.
The campaign has the backing of Lord Young, chairman of Cable and Wireless,
who as trade and industry secretary shared cabinet responsibility for the
1990 act. Others backing the campaign, launched in a letter to The Times,
include Mr David Abbott, chairman of advertising agency Abbott Mead Vickers,
and Sir Alistair Grant, chairman of food retailer Argyll.
The letter says: 'Channel 4 now pays more to ITV than it can invest in drama
and film combined. This cannot have been parliament's intention.'
It would not be unfair to make the change now, the former Channel 4 chief
executive says, because by early next year the ITV companies will have
collectively received Pounds 100m. This is 'all they estimated to get from
Channel 4 over the full period of their licences'.
