<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Obituary of Lord Joseph: The principal architect of
Thatcherism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Joseph, who died on Saturday at the age of 76, was the principal
architect of the monetarist approach to economic policy which came to be
known as Thatcherism.
This was implicitly acknowledged by Mrs Margaret (now Baroness) Thatcher in
her book The Downing Street Years when she described Lord Joseph as her
oldest political ally and 'indeed mentor'.
Both in his public and private life he will be remembered as an immensely
courteous and sometimes surprising man. At Harrow School he spent much of
his time playing cricket. As an opening batsman he twice hit a six off the
first ball, but never became more than captain of the second eleven.
At Oxford he became a fellow of All Souls' and could have had a
distinguished academic career. He could also have run the family business
Bovis, where he was briefly chairman after having insisted on starting on
the building sites and working his way up. Instead he chose politics.
Lord Joseph became a monetarist convert after serving as health and social
services secretary in the cabinet of Mr (now Sir) Edward Heath from 1970 to
1974. He was one of the big spenders when the money supply increased by 25
per cent in a single year under the chancellorship of Mr Anthony (now Lord)
Barber.
In a memorable display of candour when he moved over to the opposition front
bench after Mr Heath had led the Conservative party to its second successive
general election defeat in 1974, Lord Joseph confessed to having been an
'inflationeer'.
He further underlined the significance of the sea change in his approach to
economic policy after the interventionism of the Heath government by saying:
'I have only recently become a Conservative'.
Lord Joseph defined the object of Thatcherism as 'increasing the
inequalities' so as to provide the incentives needed to motivate
entrepreneurs and innovators at the top, and to facilitate the trickle down
effect intended to benefit those at the lower end of the income scale.
But having produced the blueprint Lord Joseph realised that he did not
possess the political steel needed for the lead role in implementing a
policy certain to face formidable opposition from the outset. In spite of
attempts by some rightwing backbenchers to persuade him to change his mind,
Lord Joseph backed away from an earlier intention to challenge Mr Heath for
the leadership of the party. Mrs Thatcher took up the gauntlet instead in
1975, and after replacing Mr Heath she relied heavily on Lord Joseph, who
had overall responsibility for policy and research, in the interval before
she became prime minister in 1979.
Their relationship continued in the seven years he served in her cabinet,
first as industry secretary, then in charge of education and science.
The initial opposition to Thatcherism came from the 'wets' in the cabinet
and on the Conservative back benches, as well as from the other political
parties.
With Mrs Thatcher happily terming sterling a 'petro-currency', the
combination of high interest rates and an over-valued pound had a sharp
impact on much of the corporate sector. Unemployment soared, company
failures increased, and Lord Joseph soon had to contend with opposition from
industry itself.
Feelings ran so high in some company boardrooms that in a speech which he
later came to regret Sir Terence Beckett, director-general of the CBI,
advocated a 'bare knuckle fight' with the government.
From the outset Lord Joseph had recognised the limitations of the policy and
spelt them out in a pamphlet entitled Monetarism is Not Enough. In this he
admitted that whereas cuts in public expenditure rarely materialised,
squeezes imposed on the private sector were 'for real'.
On those grounds Lord Joseph defended the cabinet's insistence that revenues
from North Sea oil should be used to keep down the level of taxation and the
size of the public sector borrowing requirement. He was unmoved by demands
that they should be used to counter the shrinkage in the industrial base
which resulted in Britain becoming a net importer of manufactured goods for
the first time in living memory.
In the wake of sterling's enforced exit from the European Community's
exchange rate mechanism in 1992, Lord Joseph recognised that the
manufacturing and services sector of the economy were 'too slim and too
thin' to provide the jobs and rising prosperity Britain needed. He still
maintained, however, that most of the reasons behind the decline in British
business were due to 'long-standing cultural and attitudinal causes'.
Lord Joseph was a formidable advocate of rolling back the frontiers of the
state, to reverse what he denounced as the 'ratchet' effect of socialism.
Lord Joseph's decision not to seek the leadership of the Conservative party
was also influenced by the fierce reaction to a speech in which he attacked
the 'permissive society' and the moral laxity which resulted in so many
young girls becoming unmarried mothers. He underlined the increase in the
number of births to mothers in socio-economic classes four and five who, as
a result of social deprivation, were least fitted to bring up children.
Lord Joseph's conclusion that 'the balance of our population, our human
stock, is threatened' caused uproar and he was accused of advocating
master-race theories.
His willingness to confront any issue also led him into difficulties in the
Commons when he advocated the return of capital punishment. Lord Joseph
undermined his own case by admitting that for all its deterrent effect
hanging would not be a suitable punishment for the category of murders which
were the cause of the greatest public concern at the time  - those committed
by terrorists.
Lord Joseph never shrank from admitting policy failures. For instance, he
felt deeply about the environmental and social consequences of the high-rise
building developments encouraged during his periods of office at the housing
ministry. He served as a junior minister in that department before becoming
its political head on being promoted to his first cabinet post by Harold
Macmillan in 1962.
Lord Joseph entered the Commons in 1956 after winning the safe Tory seat of
Leeds North East in a by-election.
To those who knew him the question always remained of how such a sensitive,
educated and intelligent man could go into politics and bear the opprobrium
that was thrown at him. But he did, and perhaps his character and continual
asking of questions were more important than any direct political
achievements. Lord Joseph made people think.
</TEXT>
<XX>
