<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Hurd to make statement on Pergau aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, will make a parliamentary
announcement tomorrow on the recent High Court judgment outlawing aid for
Malaysia's Pergau dam, amid indications that he will not appeal against the
decision.
Mr Hurd, due to make an announcement in a written or oral statement to the
Commons, is thought unlikely to appeal because the judgment does not affect
other development projects financed by the UK government.
An application to the Court of Appeal for permission to change the ruling
would have to be lodged by tomorrow at the latest. Whitehall officials have
privately conceded in recent weeks, however, that such a move would be
unlikely to succeed.
An official said last week: 'The basis on which we would be likely to win
the appeal would be that it was right to give aid to unsound projects.
Politically, that is a very hard case to push for.'
It has also become clear that dozens of projects in other countries financed
by the Pounds 100m a year provided under the government's aid and trade
provision scheme will not be deemed illegal under the High Court ruling.
Labour MPs will this week press Mr Hurd to give an assurance that Pounds 35m
of overseas aid money that has already been granted for the Pergau dam will
be restored to the Overseas Development Administration's budget.
They will also seek a guarantee that the remaining Pounds 170m, which
Britain is contractually bound to give Malaysia over the next nine years,
will come from other sources.
Last month the High Court ruled that grants for the Pergau project were
'fatally flawed' because the project was 'economically unsound' and did not
promote the development of a country's economy as required by trade laws.
The High Court has amplified its ruling in a full written judgment which was
delivered last week to the government and the World Development Movement,
the aid pressure group which brought the action.
According to Mr Ben Jackson, WDM's director, the full judgment specifies
that the government must find the funds for the Pergau project from other
sources.
On the financial relief given to Malaysia, the court says that 'unravelling
of some sort will be necessary, but the precise from of that unravelling is
not a matter for the court'.
The judgment also contains a statement from the Treasury solicitor,
representing the government, that 'measures will have to be taken to deal
with the unravelling of the consequences of the unlawfulness of the
decision'.
</TEXT>
