<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Revenue seeks views on tax changes for bond repo market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Inland Revenue has published a discussion paper outlining possible tax
changes which could facilitate the establishment of an open
sale-and-repurchase market for UK government bonds.
It intends to establish whether tax changes are necessary to ensure the
efficient functioning of a 'repo' market for government bonds and, if so,
how they should be best made. The possibility of setting up the market was
announced in the Budget last month.
The Revenue consultation runs in parallel with wider consultation by the
Bank of England concerning the market structure and regu-latory aspects of
an open repo system.
Both are requesting comments from market participants by January 31 1995.
A bond repo is an agreement for sale and repurchase of a bond at a
pre-arranged price. When an interest payment falls due, it is usually
received by the repo buyer rather than the security's seller.
To compensate the seller for the 'real' coupon which he has not received,
the buyer pays him what is called a 'manufactured' pay-ment.
Under present law, manufactured gilt interest payments are net of tax.
But while most investors receive their real gilt coupons net of withholding
tax, some are exempt and receive gross interest payments. These include
pension funds and charities, or foreign residents holding gilts, which are
free of tax for residents abroad.
If a repo market were introduced without accompanying tax changes, this
would throw up complications. Some investors who repo gilts across a coupon
payment date would get manufactured interest payments net of tax, even
though they usually receive gross payments.
One option proposed by the Revenue is to allow manufactured interest
payments to be paid gross. Another option is to allow gross payment of real
and manufactured gilt interest payments.
The main drawback of this, however, is a cashflow loss to the Exchequer
because the tax on the interest is collected as part of the general tax
liability of recipients some time after it is received.
To limit the cost to the Exchequer from a move to gross interest payment,
the Revenue offers four possible options: restricting gross payment to
certain gilts; restricting gross payment to certain categories of gilt
holder; introducing a system of quarterly accounting to collect tax on the
gross interest received before it would normally be assessed; or making a
charge on those who choose to receive gross interest payments.
Consultation on the Introduction of an Open Gilt Repo Market. Inland
Revenue, Financial Institutions Division, Room 510, 22 Kingsway, London WC2B
6NR.
</TEXT>
