<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Investors warned on Halifax merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Halifax and Leeds Permanent building societies will this week warn
investors that reducing their balances could affect their free share
entitlement when the merged society becomes a public limited company and a
bank.
This is likely to intensify speculation that Halifax, as the merged
organisation will be called, does not want to follow the path set by Abbey
National, the former society, which gave its investors and borrowers 100
free shares each on a 'flat-rate' basis when it converted in 1989.
Adopting a different system runs the risk of a legal challenge since it may
not fall clearly within the terms of the 1986 legislation which governs
societies.
The warning will be made in the first letter the societies are sending to
their 10m members about the merger and flotation plans announced last month.
The letters will tell members who will be eligible to vote at the special
general meetings - planned for the spring - at which the merger must be
approved if it is to go ahead.
Within each society the borrowers and the investors must separately agree to
the deal.
For the borrowers' resolution only a simple majority of those voting is
needed.
For the investors' resolution, however, three-quarters of those voting must
support the move, although there is no minimum turnout figure as there is
for investors to approve conversion.
Halifax is already the UK's biggest mortgage lender and the merger with
Leeds, the fifth biggest society, would create an organisation with about
Pounds 90bn in assets.
Members will have a separate opportunity after the merger to decide whether
the joint society should become a public limited company. The most likely
time for flotation is early 1997.
</TEXT>
