<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Visa card issuer sparks OFT probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Aggressive marketing by a consumer credit arm of the Ford motor group has
exposed a grey area in Britain's consumer protection legislation.
The Office of Fair Trading is examining a decision by The Associates, a
Windsor-based credit company controlled by Ford's US parent, to issue
unsolicited Visa credit cards.
The issue involves the rights to thousands of in-house store cards acquired
by The Associates earlier this year. Following the acquisition, The
Associates, which specialises in consumer loans, mortgages and hire
purchase, issued fully fledged Visa credit cards to the store cardholders
without their explicit consent.
The Associates said the 'upgrading' was covered by the initial terms of the
retailers' in-house cards. The OFT became involved after many cardholders
complained to local trading standards authorities that they had received
'unsolicited' cards.
According to the OFT it is an offence under the 1974 Consumer Credit Act to
send a credit card to a consumer unless the card has been previously
requested in writing. Mr Dermod Hill of the OFT said: 'A question has
arisen. We are examining it and we must now determine whether it does or
does not contravene the law.'
No one from The Associates was available for comment. It is run by
Associates Capital Corporation of Dallas.
</TEXT>
