FT  12 DEC 94 / Dollars 2bn aid pledge for Zambia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Donor nations and agencies have pledged a total of Dollars 2bn (Pounds
1.2bn) in financing assistance to Zambia for 1995. The biggest chunk of the
money, about Dollars 1.2bn, will go toward retiring arrears on International
Monetary Fund loans granted in the 1980s to the struggling African country.
About Dollars 347m will be provided for project and commodity assistance and
Dollars 441m more will be given in balance-of-payments aid. Separately, a
further Dollars 154m has been set aside for debt relief, the bank said after
a meeting in Paris of the consultative group of donor nations, the IMF and
the World Bank. The donors said support would depend on Zambia maintaining
the momentum of its recovery programme.
