<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Summit of the Americas: Chile to move soon towards Nafta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MIAMI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The first steps towards Chilean accession to the North American Free Trade
Agreement are expected to be made as soon as next week.
The Nafta members - the US, Canada and Mexico - will discuss negotiating
procedures and begin to develop entrance criteria, which will apply to Chile
and subsequent prospective members. The criteria are expected to include
macro-economic performance, adherence to multilateral trade rules, the
openness of the economy, intellectual property and investment protection.
Four-way preliminary talks are expected to begin as early as January, with
formal negotiations after a ministerial meeting to be held no later than
May. Five special committees will be set up to examine issues such as market
access measures, including rules of origin, subsidies and anti-dumping
rules, agriculture and dispute settlement.
The US said no time-frame had been set for concluding negotiations, but
Chile's finance minister, Mr Eduardo Aninat, said he hoped the accession
agreement could be signed within 14-15 months of the January start to talks.
'We think we meet virtually all the requirements to become a Nafta member,'
he said.
The US administration will start working with Congress 'early next year' to
seek 'fast track' negotiating powers. This would only be needed, it said, to
conclude the negotiations, not to begin them.
Negotiations with Chile are unlikely to provoke as much domestic opposition
as did the talks with Mexico. The Chilean economy is less than a hundredth
of that of the US, its southern hemisphere harvests do not clash so much
with those of US agricultural producers, and there are no border issues to
resolve.
Chile is also seeking associate status with Mercosur, the customs union of
Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay. Full membership of a separate
customs union is incompatible with Nafta membership, though a free trade
arrangement by Chile and Mercosur is possible. Mr Aninat expressed optimism
that progress could also be made in integration with Mercosur.
</TEXT>
