<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 94 / Honduran accord with IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD ORLEBAR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GUATEMALA CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Honduran government has signed a letter of intent with the International
Monetary Fund which will open access to Dollars 650m (Pounds 411m) in loans
from Washington-based lending institutions. The agreement follows approval
in October by the US Congress of tax reforms intended to reduce the Honduran
fiscal deficit from 11.2 per cent of GDP to 7 per cent this year, and to 4.5
per cent in 1995. The Honduran economy is expected to contract by 1.5 per
cent this year after suffering drought, energy shortages, and a drop in the
price of bananas, its main export. Without the IMF accord, the government
would have fallen behind with foreign debt obligations.
</TEXT>
